President Barack Obama has proclaimed April as National Financial Capability Month in the United States. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of financial education and empowerment for all Americans. The President highlights the appointment of Richard Cordray to lead the Consumer Finance Protection Bureau (CFPB) to ensure fair treatment for individuals in the financial industry. The government has collaborated with various industries to release the National Strategy for Financial Literacy, aiming to improve financial education across the country. The President's Advisory Council on Financial Capability (PACFC) is working to promote effective strategies for educating Americans on financial issues. The President encourages Americans to utilize the free financial resources available online and through a helpline. The proclamation urges Americans to participate in programs and activities during this month to enhance their understanding of financial principles and practices.